    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Role of Flexible Working Methods as a Career Enabler for Increasing Workforce Participation of Women in India</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Saundarya Rajesh</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Flexible Working Methods<br />Career Enabler for Increasing Workforce</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Jan-2014 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0121</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">It has often been said that the Indian Woman Professional (IWP) has not
fully utilized her talent at the workplace. This is reiterated by the fact that according
to the UNDP, at 28% the IWP’s workforce participation rate is among the lowest in
the world. A few key aspects which complicate career choices for the IWP are the
Indian joint Family system, Indian society’s collectivist outlook and the fact that the
average age at which Indian children leave home is among the highest in the world.
Many studies point to the fact that despite women’s investment in their own
education, their commitment to their management career, the shortage of
international executives and equal opportunity legislation, even today women hold
no more than a small fraction of management posts. Opportunities for women to
avail of more generous life choices seem to be lacking. And this situation persists
despite research both Indian and global - pointing to a link between gender balance
in management and corporate profitability.
Every organization that is following an aggressive growth agenda is keen on
understanding the unique career enablers which propel the workforce participation
of women in the Indian workplace. As such, there are many studies about
engagement drivers which help employees stay retained in their workplace.
However, there are no studies which speak about the career inhibitors and enablers
specific to women professionals and which have a direct impact on women’s
workforce participation.
This study, conducted in India among 1064 women professionals keen on
pursuing a career aims to uncover the linkage between women’s workforce
participation and the role that career enablers play in it, with specific focus on the
enabler of flexible working.
The analysis revealed that a majority of the women employees surveyed
belonged to the age group of below 26 years and most of them were married. A
majority of them also lived in nuclear families, corresponding to the trend of family
systems these days and a majority of them have children. The annual personal
income category that most of the women surveyed fell into was less than three lakhs.
The study also inferred that the educational qualifications of the women
professionals studied and their perception regarding flexible working were
moderately and positively associated with each other, as were the incidence of career
breaks and the perception towards work-life balance. It was found that the incidence
of career breaks and the perception of employee engagement were highly and
positively correlated with each other and career breaks and growth were also
likewise highly and positively associated with each other.
Age of the women professionals surveyed and their utilisation of flexible
working were moderately and positively associated with each other, while the
seniority of the women professionals in the organizational hierarchy and their
utilization of flexible working are moderately and negatively correlated with each
other. Regression analysis indicated that previously utilised career enablers of
mentoring, organization led skill building programmes, flexible working
arrangements, home based non family care giver and home based family member
care giver, positively influenced the different levels in the organizational hierarchy
of the women professionals at one per cent level of significance.
The results showed that the correlation co-efficient of the career strength
indicators of work-life balance and employee engagement at 0.81 were very highly
and positively associated with each other, while the career strength indicators of
work-life balance and growth were also highly and positively correlated with each
other. Meanwhile, work-life balance and longevity were seen to be highly and
positively associated with each other, while the career strength indicators of
employee engagement and growth too were positively and highly associated with
each other.
The study revealed that the career strength indicators of employee
engagement and longevity were highly and positively correlated with each other and
the indicators of growth and longevity were also likewise highly and positively
associated with each other. The various career enablers studied such as flexible
working arrangements, inspiring peer group, mentoring, home-based family member
care giver, home-based non-family care giver, organization-led skill-building
programs, self-initiated skill-building programs et al had a positive and high
association with the career strength indicator of work-life balance, while the career
strength indicator of employee engagement was moderately and positively correlated
with the various career enablers.
Meanwhile, the analysis also revealed that the career strength indicator of
growth and the various career enablers were moderately and positively associated
with each other while the career strength indicator of longevity had a moderate and
positive correlation with the various career enablers.
Canonical correlation analysis showed that the canonical loadings of career
enablers associated with the career strength indicators of the women professionals in
the order of contributions are flexible working arrangements(81.20%) organization
led skill building programmes(76.40 %), self-initiated skill building
programmes(71.30%), inspiring peer group(70.60%), mentoring(69.50%), home
based family member care giver(49.50%), home based non family care giver(47.80
per cent), day care services(38.70%), organization provided crèche(29.10%) and
other enablers(19.20%).
The first perceptual map indicated that flexible working arrangements, selfinitiated
skill building programmes, inspiring peer group, home based family
member care giver and mentoring were associated with the work-life balance of
women professionals. The second perceptual map indicated that organization led
skill building programmes, flexible working arrangements, inspiring peer group and
mentoring are associated with the employee engagement of women professionals.
The third perceptual map indicated that inspiring peer group, organization
led skill building programmes, flexible working arrangements and self-initiated skill
building programmes are associated with the growth of the women professionals,
while the fourth perceptual map indicated that inspiring peer group, organization led
skill building programmes and flexible working arrangements are associated with
the longevity of the women professionals. The path analysis indicated that the
GROWTH and LONGEVITY positively and directly influence WWFP in the order
of importance.
The study reveals the fact that the Indian Woman professional requires a
combination of Career Enablers which will help her demonstrate Career Strength
and this will enable her to stay engaged to her career and therefore increase her
participation in the workforce. The demographic profiling indicates that the woman
requires career enablers at all points of time in her career, but women belonging to
certain income groups require it more.
The provisioning of career enablers, particularly FWA (flexible working
arrangements) ensures that the woman has a positive outlook towards her
organization, engages in her work with more discretionary effort and also
demonstrates longevity of career. All of this enables her to grow in her career and
therefore maintain her continuity in the workforce</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13827">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13827</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
